properties.code: On completion of this course, students should be able to:

Describe observational findings with consistency according to the 8 principles and zang fu theoretical models and be able to interpret the meaning of these findings for Oriental differentiation of patterns.
Describe auscultation and olfactory finding and be able to interpret the meaning of these findings in terms of differentiation of patterns.
Describe palpatory findings and be able to interpret the meaning of these findings in terms of differentiation of patterns.
Conduct a coherent, smooth-flowing, comprehensive inquiry of patients, and be able to interpret the meaning of findings from their inquiry in terms of differentiation of patterns.
Upon completion of this course, students will demonstrate the following skills:

Properly prescribe the general principles of acupuncture treatments such as regulating Yin and Yang, strengthening body resistance and eliminating pathogenic factors, and distinguishing the primary from the secondary treatment based on various pathological conditions.
Recognize the treatment guidelines in various climate and seasonal condition as well as individual conditions.
Describe guidelines of six therapeutic methods such as reinforcing, reducing, warming, clearing, ascending and descending methods.

Describe the principles of point selection such as local points, adjacent/nearby points, distant points (including ipsilateral, contralateral, and bilateral points), constitutional points, symptom management points, etc.

Describe the nature of an acupuncture treatment protocol such as number of acupuncture points selection, principles for points selection, length of a treatment, frequency of a treatment, total number of acupuncture treatments for various conditions/diseases.

Be familiar with the principles of application of specific points such as Five-Shu Points, the Lower He-(Sea) points of the Six Fu Organs, The Yuan-(Primary) Points, the Luo-(Connecting) Points, the Xi-(Cleft) Points, the Eight Confluent Points, the Back-Shu Points, the Front-(Mu) Points, the Eight Influential Points.
Understand the principles of combining or paired acupuncture points.
Know of the Crossing Points selections.
Understand the treatment principles based on modern acupuncture theories.
On completion of this course, students should be able to:
Define the characteristics of the six evils, seven emotions, over-eating and over-working, retention of phlegm and blood stasis.
Communicate the basic mechanisms of exterior disease etiology, tonification and sedation, imbalance of Yin & Yang, and relationships between Qi and Blood
Be familiar with the Clean Needle Techniques (CNT) on safe practice of the taught needling techniques
Demonstrate knowledge and ability to perform moxibustion technique
Demonstrate knowledge and ability to perform cupping techniques
Demonstrate knowledge and ability to perform electroacupuncture techniques
Demonstrate knowledge and ability to perform gua sha, blood-letting, and embedded needling techniques
Understand other less commonly used acupuncture techniques such as laser acupuncture, magnet acupuncture, etc.
Be familiar with the acupuncture techniques in ancient classics, such 5 needles, 9 needles and 12 needling techniques
On completion of this course, students will be able to:
Explain Genecology and Pediatrics of the course from a Chinese Medicine perspective.
Communicate clearly the risks and contraindications for Acupuncture and Chinese Herbal Medicine in the treatment of gynecological and pediatric conditions.

Recall, describe, and develop a variety of acupuncture and herbal treatment strategies and protocols for the treatment of common gynecological complaints (such as menstrual cramps, menstrual irregularities, menopause, miscarriage & post-natal depression) and pediatric complaints (such as respiratory conditions and gastrointestinal syndromes).

*Note: Students in this course will learn both Acupuncture and Herbal treatment strategies and protocols for the covered topics. Students will not be tested on herbology treatment in the quizzes or exams.
Upon completion of this course students should be able to:
Memorize the functions and indications of major points on the Lung, Large Intestine, Stomach, Spleen, Heart, Small Intestine, and Bladder and Kidney channels.
Recognize the indications of all acupuncture points in the Lung, Large Intestine, Stomach, Spleen, Heart, Small Intestine, and Bladder and Kidney channels.

Recognize the functions and special category of specific points among these meridians such as five Shu point, Yuan-Primary points, Luo-Connecting Points, Xi-Cleft Points, Eight Confluent points, Back-Shu point, Front-Mu points, Crossing points, and Eight Influential points.
Upon completion of this course, students should be able to:
Demonstrate knowledge of musculoskeletal assessment and orthopedic examinations.
Demonstrate the ability of acupuncture treatment for orthopedic disorders of Head, Neck, Upper Extremities.
Demonstrate the ability of acupuncture treatment for orthopedic disorders of low back and pelvis.
Demonstrate the ability of acupuncture treatment for orthopedic disorders of hips and knees.
Demonstrate the ability of acupuncture treatment for orthopedic disorders of legs and feet.
Demonstrate the ability of acupuncture treatment for arthritic conditions.
Describe the indications and contraindications of orthopedic needling techniques.
Recognize when it is necessary to refer a patient to a bio-medical practitioner for further evaluation and treatment.
Be familiar with the evidence-based acupuncture practice for orthopedic disorders.
A Tooth from the Tiger’s Mouth. (2004). New York. Bisio, T.: Simon & Schuster. ISBN 978-0743245517
Upon completion of this course, the student should be able to:
Memorize the concept of “channel” in Chinese medicine.
Recognize the morphology and flow of qi in the channels.
Demonstrate understanding of the concepts of the membranes (huang), fat tissue (gao), cavities (cou li), and triple burner cavities.
Describe the general functions of the channels
Memorize the morphology, pathways and symptoms of the 12 main channels, 8 Extraordinary vessels, 15 connecting channels, 12 sinew channels, 12 divergent channels, and 12 cutaneous regions
Recognize general functions and categories of acupuncture points.
Upon completion of this course, students should be able to:
Articulate and demonstrate their understanding of basic theory, principles, patten differentiation and techniques of acupuncture for diseases of internal medicine.
Demonstrate knowledge of how to treat and prevent common internal diseases with acupuncture.
Explain the etiology, pathology, and treatment protocol of disease pathologies listed in the table below.
Review the safe practice of acupuncture.
Understand and learn evidence-based practice in acupuncture.
Upon completion of this course students will be able to:
Understand and explain Oriental Medicine dietary theories and practices.
Help advise patients on proper nutrition from an OM perspective.
Apply their learning to actual dietetic habits and prescribe foods as a way to treat and prevent disease
Communicate the relationship between theory of the Oriental Medicine and daily eating habits.
Upon completion of this course, the student should be able to:
Discuss the Basic concepts and physiology of Oriental Medicine.
Demonstrate understanding of Yin / Yang, 5 Element theory and the twelve officials as they relate to Oriental Medicine theory and applied to the nature of human beings.
Identify the Functions and basic pathology of the Zang-Fu and the functions of the curious organs.
Describe and differentiate the Eight Principles as diagnostic tools.

Recognize the functions and special category of specific points among these meridians such as five Shu point, Yuan-Primary points, Luo-Connecting Points, Xi-Cleft Points, Eight Confluent points, Back-Shu point, Front-Mu points, Crossing points, and Eight Influential points.
Upon completion of this course, students should be able to:
Memorize the functions and indications of major points on the Pericardium, San Jiao, Gallbladder, and Liver channels, Governor Vessel and Conception Vessel.
Recognize the indications of all acupuncture points in the Pericardium, San Jiao, Gallbladder, and Liver channels, Governor Vessel and Conception Vessel, as well as extra points.
On completion of this course, students should be able to:
Explain the cultural, philosophical, and historical contexts of Oriental Medicine (TCM);
Compare and contrast the Daoist, Confucian, and Legalist philosophies and explain how each of them contributed to the development of TCM;
Discuss the importance of several Chinese dynasties in terms of their contribution to the development of TCM;
Discuss the philosophical assumptions of TCM and comment on the desirability and necessity of cultural adaptation in adopting this medical system in non-Asian societies
Upon completion of this course students should be able to:
Master point location for all the points on the meridians studied. [CO1]
Identify the acupuncture points in relation to bones, nerves, vessels, tendons and muscles. [CO2]
Identify the channel pathways of each meridian in the course description. [CO3]
Communicate methods of locating acupuncture points, such as proportional measurement, anatomical landmarks, and finger measurements. [CO4]
Verbally describe and physically demonstrate location of the acupuncture points and pathways for the meridians identified in course description. [CO5]
Identify the cautions regarding the vital structures underlying all the acupuncture points, e.g. nerves, vasculature, vital organs. [CO6]

Articulate and demonstrate their understanding of basic theory, principles and herbal treatment of Traditional Chinese Internal Medicine.
Demonstrate knowledge of how to treat and prevent common internal diseases with Chinese herbal medicine.

On completion of this course, students should be able to:
Determine appropriate patient position and draping for patient comfort and treatment safety.
Select appropriate needle gauge and length and demonstrate equipment inspection and maintenance.

Needle selected points with the correct and safe insertion technique, including angle and depth of needling, and the correct removal technique in each body region such as head and neck, upper and lower limbs, and trunk (front and back).
Recite points that are contraindicated for needling in general and in specific situations (e.g., pregnancy).
Implement Clinic Hygiene, Clinic Safety procedures and policies, and for needle handling and disposal, according to CNT and OSHA guidelines
Describe Emergency Management for fainting, injury to organs, bent, stuck and broken needles and other situations that may occur in clinical settings.
On completion of this course, students should be able to:
Identify the basic anatomy of the external auricle.
Describe the somatic and vagus nerve distribution in the ear auricular acupuncture.
Identify the locations of acupoints in auricular acupuncture.
Demonstrate knowledge of functions and indications auricular acupoints, and common treatment protocols.
Demonstrate knowledge of functions and indications of scalp acupuncture points
Demonstrate knowledge and ability to safely needle auricular and scalp acupoints.
Demonstrate knowledges of functions and indications of abdominal acupuncture
Be familiar with hand acupuncture, foot acupuncture and other types of microsystems.
